  "prompt": "What is the best way of combining multiple jpegs into one jpeg/PDF on Mac OS X?",
  "response": "Combining multiple JPEG images into a single JPEG or PDF file on Mac OS X can be efficiently accomplished using Preview, the default image viewer and editor that comes with macOS. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do it:\n\n### Combining JPEGs into a Single PDF\n\n1. **Open the First Image:**\n   - Open the first JPEG image you want to combine using Preview. You can do this by double-clicking the image file, which should open it in Preview by default.\n\n2. **Add More Images:**\n   - Go to the `Edit` menu and select `Insert` > `Page from File...`. This will allow you to select additional JPEG files to add to the current document. Each new image you add will be appended as a new page in the document.\n\n3. - Repeat this process for all the images you want to combine.\n\n4. **Save as PDF:**\n   - Once all your images are combined into one document, go to the `File` menu and select `Export...`. In the export dialog, choose `PDF` as the format and select a destination to save your new combined PDF file.\n\n### Combining JPEGs into a Single JPEG\n\nIf you want to combine multiple JPEGs into a single JPEG image, the process is slightly more complex because JPEG does not natively support multiple pages like PDF. You can, however, create a single long image by stitching them together. Here\u2019s how you can do it:\n\n1. **Open the First Image:**\n   - Open the first JPEG image in Preview.\n\n2. **Adjust the First Image (if necessary):**\n   - You may want to resize or adjust the first image to ensure it fits well with the others. Use the `Tools` > `Adjust Size...` option to resize if necessary.\n\n3. **Add More Images:**\n   - Go to the `Edit` menu and select `Insert` > `Page from File...` to add more images. Each image will be added as a new page.\n\n4. **Arrange Images:**\n   - To create a single long image, you need to manually arrange the images into one continuous strip. Unfortunately, this is not straightforward in Preview for JPEG. You might need to use a third-party image editor like GIMP or Photoshop to stitch the images together more precisely.\n\n5. **Save as JPEG:**\n   - If you managed to arrange the images into one continuous strip, go to `File` > `Export...`, choose `JPEG` as the format, and save the file.\n\n### Note:\n- For creating a single JPEG, if you decide to use a third-party tool, you can export each image from Preview and then use the third-party tool to stitch them together into one image.\n\n### Alternative Method Using Automator:\n\nFor more automation, especially if you do this frequently, you can use Automator, a built-in macOS application that allows you to automate repetitive tasks.\n\n1. **Create a New Workflow:**\n   - Open Automator and choose to create a new `Workflow`.\n\n2. **Add Action:**\n   - Search for `New PDF from Images` in the action library and drag it into your workflow. This action allows you to select multiple images and combine them into one PDF.\n\n3. **Run the Workflow:**\n   - Click `Run` to execute the workflow, select your images, and it will create a combined PDF for you.\n\nUsing Preview or Automator, you can efficiently combine multiple JPEG images into a single PDF or, with some additional steps, into a single JPEG on Mac OS X.",
